  "response_text": "Sure! Here's a 3-day meal plan designed to help improve iron levels. This plan includes iron-rich foods as well as vitamin C sources to enhance iron absorption. \n\n### Day 1\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Scrambled eggs (2 eggs) with spinach (rich in non-heme iron)\n- Whole grain toast (with a spread of avocado for healthy fats)\n- Fresh orange slices (vitamin C to enhance iron absorption)\n\n**Snack:**\n- A handful of mixed nuts (cashews, almonds, and walnuts)\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Quinoa salad with black beans, diced bell peppers, corn, and a squeeze of lime (quinoa and black beans are good sources of non-heme iron)\n- Side of sliced strawberries (vitamin C)\n\n**Snack:**\n- A small apple with peanut butter\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Grilled chicken breast (heme iron source) with roasted Brussels sprouts and sweet potatoes \n- Side salad with mixed greens and cherry tomatoes (add lemon juice for dressing)\n\n---\n\n### Day 2\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Oatmeal topped with sliced bananas and a sprinkle of chia seeds (oats contain iron)\n- A glass of fortified orange juice (for vitamin C)\n\n**Snack:**\n- Carrot sticks with hummus\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Lentil soup (rich in iron) with a slice of whole grain bread\n- Side of mixed greens with lemon vinaigrette (vitamin C)\n\n**Snack:**\n- Yogurt with a handful of blueberries\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Beef stir-fry with broccoli and bell peppers, served over brown rice (beef is a great source of heme iron)\n- Side of pineapple chunks (vitamin C)\n\n---\n\n### Day 3\n\n**Breakfast:**\n- Smoothie made with spinach, banana, and fortified almond milk (spinach provides non-heme iron; fortified almond milk can provide additional nutrients)\n- A slice of whole grain toast with almond butter\n\n**Snack:**\n- A hard-boiled egg (heme iron source)\n\n**Lunch:**\n- Chickpea salad with diced cucumber, tomatoes, red onion, and a lemon-tahini dressing (chickpeas are high in non-heme iron)\n- Orange wedges on the side\n\n**Snack:**\n- Celery sticks with cream cheese\n\n**Dinner:**\n- Baked salmon (heme iron source) with a side of quinoa and steamed kale (rich in non-heme iron)\n- Roasted red bell peppers (vitamin C)\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- Pair iron-rich foods with vitamin C sources to enhance absorption.\n- Avoid drinking coffee or tea with meals, as tannins can inhibit iron absorption.\n- Consider iron-fortified cereals or snacks.\n\nThis meal plan is balanced and provides a variety of nutrients while focusing on improving iron levels. Adjust portion sizes based on individual caloric needs. Always consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian for personalized nutrition advice.",
